Your pattern is missing the closing slash, the quantifier should be 7 not 8, also you don&#39;t need the brackets and you are not using it correctly. The RegExp object has a [`.test()` method](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/RegExp/test) that can be utilized in such cases. Here is a working example:

    var pattern = /^059[0-9]{7}$/;

	if( !pattern.test(jQuery(&#39;#input_1_4&#39;).val()) ){
	    alert(&#39;Error&#39;);
	}

You check if sting starts with `059` by using `^` operator. To ensure it contains numbers only, use `\d`. Finally to ensure length 10, use `{7}`. Below is the sample code which will use `/^059\d{7}$/g` regex.


&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: false babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    $(&#39;#check_btn&#39;).click(function() {
      var text = $(&#39;#input_1_4&#39;).val();
      regExp = /^059\d{7}$/g;
      var regexMatched = (text.match(regExp) != null) ? &#39;Matched&#39; : &#39;Did not match&#39;;
    	$(&#39;#result&#39;).text(regexMatched);
    });

